title: For Sale:  Assault rifle legislation
postcontent:
Earlier this week, a comprehensive gun control package aimed at disarming and criminalizing law-abiding citizens was unveiled in Denver. While not all the proposals have been introduced, below is some of the drafted legislation that serves to punish the lawful and ignore criminals’ misuse of firearms:

House Bill 1224: Would ban the sale, transfer or possession of a magazine capable of holding more than ten rounds of ammunition. Those who currently own magazines that hold more than ten rounds would be able to keep them in their possession, but would be unable to sell or transfer them! Furthermore, any magazine larger than ten rounds that is manufactured in Colorado on or after the effective date of HB 1224 must include a serial number and date of assembly. Not only will this increase the cost of magazines, it could force law-abiding citizens who currently possess unmarked magazines larger than ten rounds to produce evidence that they possessed the magazines before the ban was enacted.

House Bill 1226: Would overturn the state Supreme Court ruling that decisively concluded that individuals who obtain a Concealed Weapons Permit cannot be denied their right to carry a firearm for self-defense on college campuses. This bill will only create more failed “gun-free zones” that are so often the target of criminals and madmen.

House Bill 1228: Would saddle law-abiding gun owners by imposing an undetermined fee (gun tax) for undergoing a background check through the Colorado Bureau of Investigation (CBI) InstaCheck system. The CBI InstaCheck program is failing in its duties and cannot process or handle the volume of checks seen in the last few months. Recently, the Colorado Legislature denied a $500,000 request from CBI to expedite the backlog of checks. Instead, HB 1228 would punish gun owners by forcing them to pay for a defunct program that blatantly impedes their constitutional right.

House Bill 1229: Would criminalize the private transfer of all firearms, even between certain family members! Under HB 1229, you will be forced to undergo a criminal investigation if you wish to purchase a firearm from certain family members, friends and co-workers. This system can only be enforced with gun registration. And, as we know from experiences in California, Canada and Australia, gun registration enables gun confiscation—only from honest citizens—since criminals are not subject to registration or submit to criminal investigations.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AK-47 (7.62x39) Pistol. M-92 (PAP) Zastava Custom, Heavily Accessorized Package
location: East of Thornton, Colorado, United States
postcontent:
I am selling a new Zastava M-92 PAP AK-47 custom pistol with13 new magazine's and well over a case of ammo. All numbers match.  I own a number of AK-47s, both rifles and pistols. I did extensive homework and research on each and every AK I own prior to purchasing them. This pistol was by far the one I looked into the most. I owed two Draco Romanian and had very little knowledge of the Zastava M-92. It did not take long to realize this pistol was a quality machine with outstanding reviews. After looking at one in person it was quite obvious that it was a far superior AK pistol than my Draco and most of my AKs. My Arsenal is the only one compatible.  Most AKs tend to fit loose and sloppy with little attention to detail. This Zastava M-92 is perfectly fitted and tight everywhere. The only complaint with them is the furniture comes very plain with no finish and often dirty which as you can see I paid a nice chunk to have mine totally refinished in Russian Red. Zastava is Serbian and considered to be one of the best AK makers if not the best period. All thier products are quality and the M 92 pistols are made new in Serbia. She has had two 30 round mags ran through her the day I got her. Unbelievable performance and extremely accurate. The following day I had her torn down and rebuilt.
The Zastava PAP M-92 was taken all the way down and each part was surprisingly well finished but not good enough for me. Each piece and component was hand worked and polished, then washed in an acid solution to remove all micro shavings.  Rivits replaced with a much more supirior rivit. The furniture was taken all the way down and redone in Russian Red Wood and a bulit proof clear coat given for an amazingly tough and beautiful finish.  The pistol grip was coated in a ruberized coating for exceptional gripping as was one of the new TapCo mags.  She comes with 13 new 30 round magazines. 7 of those are new high quality Russian steel mags. The other 6 are a variation of new TapCo 30 round mags.  She comes with just over a case of quality 7.62x39 ammo that can be seen in the photos. I have a few mags loaded with very high end penetration hollow points.  All mags in the photos are full for a total of just over 1100 rounds total.
If you just want an AK then this might not be the one for you. If you are looking for the perfect AK performance and cosmetically as well as superior quality then this is something worth looking into.

Thank you for taking the time to look. Serious buyers interested in a quality custom AK only please.

title: For Sale:  Browning Model 71 50 Alaskan For Sale
postcontent: Hello and thank you for checking out my riffle. Up for auction is a very nice Browning Model 71 lever action in .50 Alaskan, These rifles were orginally chambered in .348 Winchester. Gunsmiths wanted the Browning 71 due to its durability and strength when converting rifles to 50 Alaskan. This rifle has a half octagon half round barrel measuring at 34", an all steal Schnabel forend, the sights have not been clipped and the engraving on the barrel and action are beautiful. the stock also has a hidden compartment for holding 4 rounds. The .50 Alaskan is a wildcat cartridge developed by Harold Johnson and Harold Fuller of the Kenai Peninsula of Alaska in the 1950s. Johnson based the cartridge on the .348 Winchester in order to create a rifle capable of handling the large bears in Alaska. Design: Harold Johnson necked out the .348 Winchester case to accept a .510" diameter bullet, and Harold Fuller developed the barrel, marrying a .50 caliber barrel to an old Winchester Model 1886 rifle. Since the rifle was designed for use on Alaska’s great bears, Johnson cut 720-grain (47 g) boat-tail .50 BMG bullets in half, seating the 450-grain (29 g) rear half upside down in the fireformed .50-caliber case. It didn’t take Johnson long to find out that the 450-grain truncated shaped “solid” would shoot through a big brown bear from any direction, claiming in 1988, “I never recovered a slug from a bear or moose, no matter what angle the animal was shot at. Harold’s favorite load in the .50 Alaskan was 51.5 grains (3.34 g) of IMR-4198 with a Barnes 400-grain (26 g) flatnose ,jacketed bullet for about 2,100 ft/s (640 m/s) and just under 4,000 ft·lbf (5,400 J)of muzzle energy Shipping/handling is going to be $55 and insurance will be added at 1.75% of the item's value to cover potential damage or loss of the item in shipping. The price is for $1500 therefore, this item will still be subject to shipping and insurance charges. Because of additional paperwork and time to process the shipment
